      <figcaption>We compare materials, coatings, heat behavior, and real-world use.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure class='media'>
      <picture>
        <source srcset="/assets/img/pan-crosssection-880x600.avif" type="image/avif">
        <img src="/assets/img/pan-crosssection-880x600.webp" width="880" height="600" alt="Titanium pan cross-section showing base and coating layers" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
      </picture>
      <figcaption>Titanium construction varies — pure Ti vs titanium‑reinforced coatings. Check the spec sheet.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <div class='quick-answer'>
      <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
      <p><strong>Choose titanium</strong> for light, responsive pans that stand up to daily cooking (pure Ti vs titanium-reinforced coatings varies). <strong>Choose ceramic</strong> if you want slick, PTFE-free nonstick for eggs and gentle sauté—accepting shorter coating life and gentler heat.</p>
      <p>For deeper claims, see <a href='/titanium-cookware-myths-2025/'>Titanium Cookware Myths (2025)</a> and our full <a href='/titanium-cookware-guide/'>Titanium Cookware Guide</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

