  <section class='wrap' id='how-differ'>
    <div class='card'>
      <h2>How titanium and ceramic differ</h2>
      <div class='grid cols-2'>
        <div>
          <h3>Titanium (and titanium-reinforced)</h3>
          <p>“Titanium cookware” can mean <strong>pure titanium</strong> (ultra-light, may develop hot spots) or <strong>aluminum/steel bases with titanium-reinforced coatings</strong> for added hardness. Performance depends on base metal + coating system. See our <a href='/best-titanium-pans-2025/'>Best Titanium Pans 2025</a> roundup for examples.</p>
          <figure class='media'>
            <picture>
              <source srcset="/assets/img/titanium-sear-900x600.avif" type="image/avif">
              <img src="/assets/img/titanium-sear-900x600.webp" width="900" height="600" alt="Searing steak in a titanium-reinforced nonstick skillet at medium-high heat" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
            </picture>
            <figcaption>Searing performance depends on base thickness and coating system.</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Ceramic (sol-gel)</h3>
          <p>Most “ceramic” pans use a sol-gel coating. They feel very slick when new and can brown nicely at medium heat. Overheating and abrasive scrubbing shorten life; gentle care extends it. If you’re deciding between brands, check our <a href='/brand-comparisons/'>brand comparisons</a>.</p>
          <figure class='media'>
            <picture>
              <source srcset="/assets/img/ceramic-eggs-900x600.avif" type="image/avif">
              <img src="/assets/img/ceramic-eggs-900x600.webp" width="900" height="600" alt="Ceramic nonstick pan releasing eggs at medium heat" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
            </picture>
            <figcaption>Ceramic shines at low-to-medium heat for delicate foods.</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class='wrap' id='table'>
    <div class='card'>
      <h2>Comparison table</h2>
      <table class='table compare'>
        <caption>Material trade-offs at a glance (generalized; verify per product)</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr><th scope='col'>Criteria</th><th scope='col'>Titanium</th><th scope='col'>Ceramic</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th scope='row'>Weight</th><td>Usually lighter; pure Ti and thin-walled pans feel nimble.</td><td>Varies; many are aluminum-based and moderate in weight.</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope='row'>Heat response</th><td>Fast; pure Ti can have hot spots; layered bases improve evenness.</td><td>Evenness depends on the base; best results at medium heat.</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope='row'>Nonstick feel</th><td>“Titanium-reinforced PTFE” behaves like classic nonstick.</td><td>Very slick when new; can lose glide sooner under harsh use.</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope='row'>Utensils &amp; cleaning</th><td>Generally resilient; still avoid harsh scouring to protect coatings.</td><td>Use soft tools; avoid abrasive pads to preserve the sol-gel layer.</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope='row'>Induction support</th><td>Only if the base is magnetic (steel plate or steel body).</td><td>Only if a magnetic base is added; many are not induction-ready.</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope='row'>Longevity</th><td>Strong when coating/base are quality; avoid thermal shock.</td><td>Great first months; lifespan hinges on heat discipline and care.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <figure class='media'>
        <picture>
          <source srcset="/assets/img/compare-matrix-1000x600.avif" type="image/avif">
          <img src="/assets/img/compare-matrix-1000x600.webp" width="1000" height="600" alt="Matrix comparing weight, heat response, nonstick, and induction readiness for titanium vs ceramic" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
        </picture>
        <figcaption>At-a-glance differences. Always verify specs for each specific pan.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <p class='small'>Verify whether “titanium” means <em>pure Ti</em> or a <em>titanium-reinforced coating</em>. Cross-link: <a href='/titanium-cookware-myths-2025/'>2025 myths guide</a> and our <a href='/care-and-cleaning/'>care &amp; cleaning hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class='wrap' id='who-which'>
    <div class='card'>
      <h2>Who should pick which?</h2>
      <div class='grid cols-2'>
        <div>
          <h3>Pick titanium if you…</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Value light, nimble pans and quick temperature changes.</li>
            <li>Want classic nonstick behavior on titanium-reinforced PTFE lines.</li>
            <li>Cook protein sears at medium-high and finish in the oven. See <a href='/best-titanium-pans-2025/'>best titanium pans</a> for tested picks.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Pick ceramic if you…</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Prefer PTFE-free nonstick for eggs and delicate foods.</li>
            <li>Cook mostly at low-to-medium heat and avoid sprays/abrasives.</li>
            <li>Don’t mind replacing the pan when the glide eventually fades. Compare with options in our <a href='/brand-comparisons/'>brand comparisons</a>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class='wrap' id='care'>
    <div class='card'>
      <h2>Care &amp; cleaning</h2>
      <div class='grid cols-2'>
        <div>
          <h3>Titanium</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Preheat gently; upshift heat gradually.</li>
            <li>Avoid thermal shock (very cold rinse on very hot pan).</li>
            <li>Hand-wash; soft sponge; avoid steel wool on coated interiors. More details: <a href='/care-and-cleaning/'>care &amp; cleaning guide</a>.</li>
          </ul>
          <figure class='media'>
            <picture>
              <source srcset="/assets/img/titanium-sponge-wash-900x600.avif" type="image/avif">
              <img src="/assets/img/titanium-sponge-wash-900x600.webp" width="900" height="600" alt="Hand-washing a titanium-coated pan with a soft sponge" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
            </picture>
            <figcaption>Hand-wash with a soft sponge to preserve the coating.</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Ceramic</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Keep to low-medium heat; avoid empty-pan preheats on high.</li>
            <li>No aerosol sprays; use a dab of oil/butter if needed.</li>
            <li>Soak, then soft sponge. Skip abrasive powders and pads. See <a href='/care-and-cleaning/'>ceramic care tips</a>.</li>
          </ul>
          <figure class='media'>
            <picture>
              <source srcset="/assets/img/ceramic-low-heat-900x600.avif" type="image/avif">
              <img src="/assets/img/ceramic-low-heat-900x600.webp" width="900" height="600" alt="Cooking gently over low heat with a ceramic nonstick pan" loading="lazy" decoding="async">
            </picture>
            <figcaption>Gentle, even heat helps ceramic coatings last longer.</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class='wrap' id='faqs'>
    <div class='card'>
      <h2>FAQs</h2>
      <details><summary>Is titanium cookware always nonstick?</summary><div>No. Pure titanium has no nonstick on its own; most home pans rely on a coating (often PTFE, sometimes marketed as titanium-reinforced). See <a href='/titanium-cookware-guide/'>Titanium Cookware Guide</a>.</div></details>
      <details><summary>Is ceramic safer?</summary><div>Ceramic coatings are PTFE-free. Safety depends on proper use: moderate heat, no abrasives, and intact surface. Compare durability in our <a href='/brand-comparisons/'>brand comparisons</a>.</div></details>
      <details><summary>Will either work on induction?</summary><div>Only if there’s a magnetic base. Check the spec sheet or try a fridge magnet on the bottom. For induction-ready picks, visit <a href='/best-titanium-pans-2025/'>best titanium pans</a>.</div></details>
    </div>
  </section>

